description.text:
The Openscad script below allows for the printing of custom spool holders for the Makerbot Replicator. These holders not only allow for different spindle widths and depths but also a different offset from the support holes in the back of the Replicator. You can thus print with different spools than those supplied by Makerbot. The design allows for printing without support to give as much strength as possible to the spool holders. Update 5th April 2013:
  • Added a new 15mm collar to strengthen bottom of spool holder.
  • Added customizer.
  • Added recommended print settings.

If you don't want to use Customizer then you need to modify the Openscad script to match your spool. You should be able to start by changing the 2 variables SpoolHoleDiameter and SpoolDepth. The rest of the parameters can be left to begin with. Depending on your print quality you may need to adjust the calculations for the tube baseplate. Generate your STLs via Openscad. I have found it easier to print the wall support and tube separately. There is an option in the script for this. The design does not need any support to print. The tube base plate needs to be as flat as possible to slide into the wall support. You may need to sand the base plate edges. It can be a tight fit to begin with and then loosen up a bit. It is possible to snap the tube off trying to extract a stubborn base plate from the wall mount. The sample STLs are for spool holders which should fit the supplied Makerbot spools. You will need to mirror the wall support in RepG for the right side spool on the Replicator. The subtle rounding on the top edges of the wall mount is necessary to allow for easier spinning of the spools. I have found the following settings work well for printing with Makerware ABS: Infill: 35%
Layer Height: .27mm
Number of Shells: 2
Feedrate: 80
Travel Feedrate: 100
Raft: yes

title: Replacement Depressor for Truck Systems Technology 507 Sensor
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a part to repair the worn depressor inside of my failed Truck Systems Technology, RV 507 Sending unit. They appear to be one of the only ones on the market that have a plastic depressor instead of rubber or brass. The plastic gets splayed when tightened against the dill pin in the tire valve stem. As sold by Truck Systems Technology...you'll pay about $109 for a 2-pack.

If you're in the market for a TPMS system for your truck, trailer, 5th wheel, motor home...look somewhere OTHER than TST. At least look at the sensor to make sure it's built to last longer than these where.

If you've already swallowed the bait...and you have splayed depressors to contend with...then print a few of these to get them sending again.

To use...

1) Remove the Sensor.
2) Using a dental pick...remove the rubber washer inside.
3) With a drill bit or dremel tool...remove the splayed/malfunctioning depressor..flush with the bottom of the threaded opening.
4) Place a gasket over the newly printed depressor.
5) Using a spare valve stem...with the valve removed...as an assembly tool...thread the TPMS sendsor onto the stem...a bit at a time...on and off until the depressor and rubber washer are full seated.
6) Return you sensor to your Truck or RV and enjoy a little more life from the otherwise shot sensor.

CAUTION: This modification will void your warranty. So, see if they are willing to offer you any solution under warranty before modifying any of your equipment. In my case...they only offered to sell me another complete sending unit.

title: RC4WD 9.5cti Winch Mount for Axial Wraith

description.text:
I needed a mount for the RC4WD 9.5cti 1/10 Winch that would fit in the front of the Axial Wraith. Sadly, the winch seems to be a bit too large/tall to fit under the support struts. So, I made this little thing so the winch can be mounted directly onto the supports.

This has the benefit of freeing up space to mount the headlamps in the front bumper. protecting them better and have them no longer in front of the servo mount.

It's my first try at 3D Printing and Design, but maybe someone will find this useful.

There are 2 holes on each side if you decide to use dril into the supports to secure them in place. That being said, I found that it is not really needed. I coated the inside of the holes with ShoeGoo and it's plenty secure.

description.text:
UPDATE, PLEASE READ: --------------------------------------------------------------------
2/13/17- Though the concept does work, after some load testing and some backlash testing on this gearbox i realized that my decision to round off the gear teeth (intended for easy printing) was a very bad one. This gearbox has excessive backlash and the rounded teeth actually causes the gears to go crooked in the gearbox and bind it up, almost completely taking away the gear ratio advantage. I have learned from this failure and make better "things" since.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2054378
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2101218

For any instructions i have missed, please refer to the larger version, they should be helpful to you (until i can get a new video made), they are very similar except this one needs to have the planet gears arranged as shown in the picture above
Heres the larger version
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2054378

//---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PARTS NEEDED

-The 18 Tooth Ring Gear
-The 19 Tooth Ring Gear
-The Planet Gears, ( I printed the The Less Backlash Gears, the others are for if you have fitment issues)
-The NEMA 17 Mount.

You must not use both D-Shaft Sun Gears in this gearbox unless you cut your shaft shorter!
-For a 50.4:1 Ratio Choose the 5 Tooth D Shaft Sun Gear and the 6 Tooth Clearance Sun Gear
-For a 38.75:1 Ratio Choose the 6 Tooth D Shaft Sun Gear and the 5 Tooth Clearance Sun Gear
//---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
INSTRUCTIONS FOR ASSEMBLY!

There is Alignment Marks on all gears this time. Please Refer to the pictures above, (They are Small Circles, either inset, or extruded.

Always Check where the Flat Spot is on the Sun gear and D-Shaft before installing it.
Always Insert the gear set into the housing with the D-Shaft Sun gear facing the Motor.

The attachment is used to make it easier to put in and take out a plug from a socket. This could be a very helpful aide for people with arthritis, lower dexterity, lower mobility and injuries to the wrist or lower strength. Print one for appliances that are taken out often - hairdryers, kitchen gadgets, lamps etc. I now use my feet to plug in my printer so I don't have to bend down beneath my desk all the time!

TO MAKE:

  • 1 x M6 nut
  • 1 x M6 HEX bolt 40mm long.
  • 1 x Appliance with a UK plug (T-Plug) (this wont fit all UK plugs, mine came from Wilko though)
    • Printed parts. PLA works fine for this.

TO ASSEMBLE:
1 - Place M6 nut placed into the clip's hexagonal hole
2 - Snap the clip over the back of you plug, with a bit of force it will click into place.
3 - Now place the 40mm HEX M6 bolt through the handle.
4 - Finally screw in the handle to the clip.

title: Ergodox thumb keys stabilizer mounting plate

description.text:
Whether you assembled your ergodox wrong or intentionally omitted the plate, you may still want the ability to use stabilizers for the 2u keys on each side. This model started by cutting out the appropriate area from Diomedia_be's design and then tweaking it until my plate-mount stabilizers fit and were in the correct position. There's a bit of a chamfer to clear small solder bumps from through-hole diodes as well.

Should print on just about any 3d printer without support.

Why would I assemble my ergodox wrong on purpose, though? Well, using pcb-mount switches gives enough stability for most of the switch positions without needing a plate, I thought a bare PCB might look cool, and I plan to tinker with this one a lot... e.g. adding new electronics like an LCD, writing my own firmware.

UPDATE: Apparently 0.5mm makes a huge difference in whether or not a stabilizer binds up when you push a key down. Uploaded a new version 6 of the files to address this issue.

title: Sunhokey firmware configuration.h for MKS gen 1.4 UPDATED

description.text:
Be ready to power down the printer if the firmware doesn't work
Please read the warning section in its entirety before use.

This is the configuration.h file for Repetier firmware. Someone asked about it so here it is. Go to repetier.com/firmware/v092/ and upload the included file. Change settings as necessary and download the complete firmware. Open the project file under Arduino IDE make sure you select the atmega 2560 and the right port. Upload and make sure the board is wired correctly.

Primary picture is of the 1.2 I think, but the boards are pretty much the same.
The picture is correct as far as wiring goes, the second z motor goes into E1
The hot bed heater goes on the top left screw mounts and E0 goes into the third position.

You may have to change the thermosistors used according to what you've got. Baud rate is set to 115200.

Updated 6-22-17 set eeprom value to 99, will overwrite eeprom values
Added warning section
Elaborated on use
Corrected information

WARNING

The original PCB heater, and any PCB heater, as far as I'm concerned, are huge fire risks due to the soldering joints attaching wires. Please do not use them. Replace them with good silicone heaters or do not use them. The purpose of this file is to get people into using the Repetier online configuration tool. It is an easy one to use and is the first crack people should get into editing firmware. I only provide the configuration file to upload as a guide. You are supposed to change the values yourself and learn something in the process. It is already configured for our personal printer. That means it has the Dildahmetron and Phistterbut_Inc branding as well as e steps tuned for our custom direct drive system, not the original bowden. Again, I am not going to be held responsible for your house fire, this is a simple guide to teach and isn't even complete firmware.
Thank you.

description.text:
For LG840G Cell Phones

See also my version without the ipod-shuffle case. Just a cover. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:658862

Wanted to make use of my new ipod Shuffle and have with me when i wanted it. Use it sometimes plugged into my car stereo.

It prints fine. One thing to think of before printing is, to print separately. Do so because the phone-Clip part that pushes down over the ipod case part needs to print slower, about 20 to 30mm/s, while the case pictured was printed at 80mm/s. The phone-clip has the thin small finger clips which need to print slowly.

Works out nice because the phone-clip part will wear out with a finger clip breaking after a few months of pocket use. They print quickly.

Don't forget to use support for the phone-clip. Hate it, but the only way i could think to get all parts in and printable. You may have some areas that may need gluing some velvet or paper in to give a bit of more holding on the ipod case part. For a more of a snap in effect.

Hope you enjoy, Rick.

Note: The picture shows a small piece of thin card stock glued inside the top finger on the phone-clip part. The updated version 4 with the download should fix this without any card stock needed.

Update: Also wanted to add that the fingers may print a bit loose and not have the snap-in on the phone you may want. The thing i did with mine is; use a micro torch or maybe a hair drier to warm the top single finger and squeeze it in a bit. Should work fine and have the snap-in you like.

description.text:
Y adapter piece for dual extrusion prints on a bowden system

M6 threaded adapters are used.
M3 x 10mm screws are used to hold the unit together

The unit is in two pieces so as to aid in cleaning if needed. And it is stronger than one piece setups.

The threads will actually print at M6. I can make other designs if required.

Simplify 3d tool change script, borrowed and edited from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1926351

G90
G1 X ...xlocation Y ...ylocation F4800; Move X Y for tool change
T[old_tool]; Select Old Tool
G92 E0; Zero Extruder
G91; Relative Coordinates
G1 E-15 F3600; Fast Retract 15mm
G4 P600
G1 E13 F3600; Fast Reinsert 13mm
G1 E-13 F3600; Fast Retract 13mm
G4 P1000; Pause 1secs
G1 E-100 F3600; Fast long retract
G90; Absolute Coordinates
G92 E0; Zero Extruder
T[new_tool]; Select New tool
G92 E0; Zero Extruder
G91; Relative Coordinates
G1 E110 F3600; Fast insert 110mm
G1 E5 F300; 5mm/s Feed 5mm
G92 E0; Zero Extruder
G90; Absolute Coordinates

My x location and y location is set manually to be in the centre of the prime tower. This way and oozing, or extra prime is in the centre of the tower. This then is levelled and nozzle cleaned by the little blob as it prints the prime tower

My overall retraction is set to 115mm. But yours can be much less. I find its best to bring the filament back into the Bowden tube so you can see where it is. You can also then see the plug on the end, and you can see where you need to set the second colour when initially loading.

In Marlin you need to enable 2 extruders, and enable single nozzle.

You need to have one hotend and one thermister defined also, not two.

I find the best bowden adapters are the ones that allow a 4mm ptfe tube to go all the way through them. You can then Chamfer the inside edges of the ptfe tube to minimise any blockages. And you can have the PTFE tube run all the way to the plastic chamfered section of the splitter.

title: Algebra: Adding and Subtracting Linear Expressions

description.text: This activity uses algebra tiles to add and subtract linear expressions with integer coefficients.
I used TinkerCad to create a rectangle that I put an 'x' hole in and a square that I put a '1' hole in.
CCSS

This lesson will meet the following standard: CCSS.Math.Content.7.EE.A.1
Apply properties of operations as strategies to add, subtract, factor, and expand linear expressions with rational coefficients. In this lesson students will learn how to add and subtract linear expressions with integer coefficients.

Start this activity by guiding students through an example. We want to add (2x+3) + (x+1). Show them how to set up these two expressions [Figure 1]. Next, have students count or group together all of the x’s to see that there are a total of three and do the same for the ones to see a total of four. They should write out the result as 3x + 4. Once they see how this works students can work on more examples on their own or in groups. Then, guide students through a subtraction example. To subtract (2x+3) – (x+1) take away from the first group the number of x’s and 1’s in the second. We are left with x + 2 [Figure 2]. See the files section for a handout. Figure 1 Figure 2
• algebra
one class period

Print these manipulatives out a ahead of time. The amount you need to print will depend on how many students you have and if you want them to work in groups. If you want students to be able to add a lot of x's and 1's together you may want to print 30 of each per student/group.

This is a 1:20 scale model of a Triceratops prorsus skeleton. The source model was provided thanks to Thingiverse user Ravelios. The Triceratops prorsus was thought to have reached 9 meters in length, and so this model when assembled is ~45cm long. Instructions for assembly are included in the files. More information on the Triceratops is available on Wikipedia (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triceratops)

Using Meshmixer, I posed the skeleton into a walk and curved the tail for a more natural look. I broke the model into printable pieces and added connecting pins and sockets for a mostly snap together assembly. Some glue may be required however. The base was created from scratch.

This is a training tool used to teach people about Lock picking. It allows you to visualize and feel what a binder pin is and how to detect one vs a non binder pin.

Assembly:
-Put pins into base unit with a spring under each one
-You can use a spring from a pin or 3d print one of your own from any number of sources.
-Place top piece over base unit and align pins to they fit thru holes.
-Slider bar fits in side hold and slides into the pins

The slider bar represents the lock core rotating and causing the pin to "Bind"
The pins are offset intentionally to demonstrate the small variations in actual locks "the reason we are able to pick lock in the first place"

Press the slider bar against the pins laterally
As it hits the Pins, only one will "Bind" you can press it down causing that pin to be "Set"
The slider bar will then advance to next binding pin
After all pins are set the slider bar will cover up all pins representing an open lock

This is still a work in progress. Lots of hours spent testing and reprinting.
Let me know if i can change anything to help facilitate an easier print.
Send me a tip or buy me a beer if you enjoy this design
Thanks

description.text:
This is a Serpinski Pyramid with 4 Triangle faces. Each face adds an iteration of the Serpinski Triangle fractal.

Face 1 = solid
Face 2 = 3 solid triangles, 1 hole triangle
Face 3 = 9 solid triangles, 4 hole triangles
Face 4 = 27 solid triangles, 13 hole triangles

Added Optional "SerpinskiPyramidConnectors01.stl" file to help glue these together to continue the iterations.

(Optional) To iterate by stacking these:

  1. Print 4 Pyramids
  2. Print 6 connectors
  3. Stack Pyramids and glue on connectors as pictured to brace them in place.
  4. Do steps 1 to 3 x 4 for each new iteration and stack as large as you dare.

Warning: Scaling this item can result in very weak joints between the internal triangles. I recommend printing at 100% scale. I did manage to print a 50% scale version but needed some super glue to reinforce the triangle bonds.

description.text:
Version 2.15 "Not That Final Apparently" - Details in Misc Notes...

Star Wars: Imperial Assault is a pretty great tabletop/board game, but it is lacking in a few areas that could do with improvement. One of those areas is keeping track of groups of identical figures like Storm Troopers or Imperial Guards. I mean, stickers? Really, Fantasy Flight?

So, inspired by The_Lair's version of numbered bases, I fired up Fusion 360 and made a series of base pieces that your Imperial Assault small figures can be slotted into. Each base has a cluster of pips placed at 90° from each-other to denote individuals: 1 by 4 pips for #1, 2 by 4 pips for #2, 3 by 4 pips for #3, and 4 by 4 pips for #4. I highly recommend painting the base and/or pips to keep track of your groups/squads by color.

Files Included:

  • Single Base 1x4
  • Single Base 2x4
  • Single Base 3x4
  • Single Base 4x4
  • Arrangement of 2x of each base type (8)
  • Arrangement of 4x of each base type (16)

I formerly printed with a New Matter MOD-t, so for MOD-t users I have included pre-made gcode files in a ZIP container except for the 16 piece file as it will not fit the MOD-t print bed. For all others, just pop the stl files into your favorite slicer — I recommend Cura — and have at it!

title: Dual Motion Fidget Spinner
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Yet another fidget spinner...
My take on the tend utilizes skate ball bearings (designed for Bones REDZ, but will likely fit many similar bearings) as per usual. It also uses two resistance bands (two Viton O-Rings until I find a better option) that attach through the central body to both wings. The model has a revolving slider mechanism that allows the wings to each revolve a total of 70 degrees around the central bearing. When combined with the resistance bands it means you can spin it around as well as fold the unit in a jack knife fashion.

I have yet to print this myself yet, making it a work in progress. If anyone beats me to the punch please let me know if you encounter any problems.

I eventually plan on tweaking this model so that the core body snaps together instead of needing to be adhered together.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 5

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Print 6 bearing plugs, two of each wing insert, and one of each wing and the core body halves.

Closing In The Resistance Bands Within The Wings

The bands need to be attached to the two wings first and foremost. If you haven't done so already, remove any support structures clinging to the wings. Place a band in each of the grooves in one of the wings. Then slide the respective inserts into the wing, closing the resistance bands in. Use your preferred adhesive to lock the inserts in place. Repeat the process on the other side of the bands with the other wing.

Assemble The Main Body

One the wings are fitted with the resistance bands it's time to get them enclosed in the main central body. Start by sanding the core body halves where they will end up meeting so that they fit flat against each other. Place the slider arm of each wing into the side cavities of the bottom half of the core body. Maneuver the bands over the bottom half of the core body by threading them around the inner perimeter and press the top half of the core body over them. Use your preferred adhesive again to attach the top half and the bottom half of the core body together.

Pop In The Ball Bearings

Press a ball bearing into each cavity. If they end up moving around, use your preferred adhesive to lock them in place (just don't get any into the bearing). Loctite STIK'N Seal Outdoor Adhesive works pretty well for me when bonding metals to plastics. Next Press a bearing plug into each side of the bearings (or leave them off if you'f like a slimmer model.

Enjoy.

02-02-2017

Hey sorry I didn't make this updates section sooner.

A few days ago I updated the slider mechanism on both wing files. Upon printing them myself I realized some difficult-to-sand areas (the slider plate and the extension connecting it to the wing) were frustrating me. So the plate is a little thinner now and the extension is as well (it was catching against the core body). Hopefully it will require less post-processing.

After printing the wing inserts I realize they are pretty small and might be troublesome on some printer models. I may end up making the inserts larger to remedy this. If you guys agree, let me know.

I Printed mine in PETG, but I think PLA would also work.

Using the Tool

You'll need a thin sheet of metal (appx. 0,2mm). I used an empty tube of mayonnaise.

  1. Place the metal between the tool.
  2. Cut the metal so that you have at least 1cm around the tool
  3. Press the Tool together. Either step onto the tool or use a vise
  4. Use the bottom part to poke a hole through the metal
  5. Deburr and remove unneeded metal around the hole
  6. Cut 3 arms that will hold the metal on the stock shroud
  7. install
  8. Enjoy using the Fan again :)

IMPORTANT: The nozzle MUST show through the shroud. If it is too close you will damage your print!

title: MP Select Mini Combo Filament Filter and Guide

description.text:
This is for the Monoprice MP Select Mini, a filament guide and filter combined.
So this is my first creation, it's sort of a remix I guess, but something new really as I had to do quite a bit of work to make it all work correctly. I used Meshmixer and took two parts and created single part that I wanted. I liked both parts and actually put them together manually with glue and a screw but I decided I wanted to created a new part altogether.
This combines these two:
Monoprice MP Select Mini Filament Guide
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1776779
Filament Dust Filter
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:190118

I combined these but had to do extra work to make it fit correctly. When I created the first one I had to cut and melt and bend to fit everything together, but now I just took all of that knowledge from that build and came up with this combo for the MP Select Mini.

You will find the filter box is tight to open, it's made that way as just opening and closing it a few times will loosen the clasp. You don't want the clasp very loose as I found that the filament can actually pop the box open.

Edit: I uploaded another STL file with a larger hole in the back section of the top of the box. I had forgot to enlarge the hole there. Because of the angle of the filament going in it tends to rub, this should fix that now.

Printer:

monoprice mp select mini

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

50

Notes:

Originally I did 20% infill but found that after a while the guide started to bend from the filament pulling down on it so I found that at least 50% infill stops that.
I wanted a nice looking part so I used .1 layer height which came out very nice.
Supports, yes just touching buildplate for the top of the filter box.
For raft just use brim to make sure it stays in place as it's rather thin.

Note to install.

Notes for installation... Yes you can use existing screws to attach bar to printer. The screw holes slightly smaller so you may have to remove some material, better to be smaller than too large, easier to remove than add material as it were. I just used an X-Acto knife and spun it around the holes top and bottom a few times and it removed enough material, just a few seconds really.

The bottom of the box is cut to allow the screw to go in, but the top is not. You have to install with the box in the open position.
